//! # milkdropper-preset
//!
//! Safe, fast expression evaluator and .milk preset parser for Milkdropper.
//!
//! This crate provides a **sandboxed**, **bytecode-compiled** expression language
//! for animating visualization presets. It replaces the legacy ns-eel2 C library
//! with 100% safe Rust code.
//!
//! ## Features
//!
//! - **Safe**: No unsafe code, no memory corruption, no crashes
//! - **Fast**: Bytecode compilation (~100-500ns per instruction)
//! - **Sandboxed**: No file I/O, no system calls, instruction limits
//! - **Compatible**: Supports existing .milk preset syntax
//!
//! ## Architecture
//!
//! ```text
//! .milk file → Parser → Expressions → Lexer → Tokens
//!                                            ↓
//!                                          Parser → AST
//!                                            ↓
//!                                        Compiler → Bytecode
//!                                            ↓
//!   Audio Data → PresetContext → VM (Execute Bytecode) → Updated Variables
//! ```
//!
//! ## Example Usage
//!
//! ```rust,no_run
//! use milkdropper_preset::{PresetEngine, PresetContext};
//!
//! // 1. Create engine and load preset
//! let mut engine = PresetEngine::new();
//! engine.load_preset("presets/example.milk")?;
//!
//! // 2. Create context and inject audio data each frame
//! let mut ctx = PresetContext::new();
//! ctx.bass = 0.8;      // From Phoenix Marine audio analyzer
//! ctx.mid = 0.5;
//! ctx.treb = 0.3;
//! ctx.bass_att = 0.6;
//! ctx.time = 1.5;
//!
//! // 3. Execute preset expressions (per-frame)
//! engine.evaluate_frame(&mut ctx)?;
//!
//! // 4. Use computed variables for rendering
//! let zoom = 1.0 + ctx.q[0] * 0.1;   // q1 controls zoom
//! let rotation = ctx.q[1];            // q2 controls rotation
//! # Ok::<(), Box<dyn std::error::Error>>(())
//! ```
//!
//! ## Expression Language
//!
//! ### Variables (Read/Write)
//! - Audio: `bass`, `mid`, `treb`, `bass_att`, `mid_att`, `treb_att` (read-only)
//! - User: `q1`-`q32`, `t1`-`t8` (persistent across frames)
//! - Parameters: `zoom`, `rot`, `cx`, `cy`, `dx`, `dy`, `warp`, etc.
//! - Time: `time`, `frame`, `fps` (read-only)
//!
//! ### Operators
//! - Arithmetic: `+`, `-`, `*`, `/`
//! - Assignment: `=`
//! - Grouping: `(`, `)`
//!
//! ### Functions
//! - Trig: `sin(x)`, `cos(x)`
//! - Math: `sqrt(x)`, `abs(x)`
//!
//! ### Example Expressions
//! ```text
//! q1 = bass + bass_att * 0.5;
//! zoom = 1.0 + q1 * 0.2;
//! rot = rot + 0.05 * sin(time);
//! wave_r = 0.5 + bass * 0.5;
//! ```
//!
//! ## Safety Guarantees
//!
//! - **No infinite loops**: Instruction count limit (10,000/frame)
//! - **No stack overflow**: Pre-allocated stack with depth checking
//! - **No division by zero**: Returns 0.0 on division by zero
//! - **No NaN propagation**: Checks for invalid math operations
//! - **No buffer overflows**: All array accesses are bounds-checked
//!
//! ## Performance
//!
//! - Compilation: ~10-20μs per expression (one-time at preset load)
//! - Execution: ~5-50μs per frame for typical preset (50-100 instructions)
//! - Budget: <1ms per frame at 60fps (leaves 15ms for rendering)

// Public API modules
mod context;
mod engine;
mod error;
mod preset;
mod parser;

// Expression evaluation (internal)
pub(crate) mod eval;

// Public exports
pub use context::{PresetContext, VarIndex};
pub use engine::PresetEngine;
pub use error::{PresetError, VMError};
pub use preset::Preset;

// Re-export commonly used types
pub use eval::bytecode::Program;
pub use eval::vm::VM;

